 | <a href="javascript:ce_enforce('17','000018','000008');">Problem??</a>
  </FONT>
<HR size="1" color="#3299CC">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Green fields.  Verdant green fields.  Looking around I don't recognize anything.  Surprised, I look again.  Nope.  Definitely a new area.<P>Scalpels body is practically at my feet.  Kneeling, I check for a pulse that I know is not there.  The body has been ripped asunder, but it is still warm.<P>"Gort!" I shout. "Can you hear me?"<P>"Hey der!" comes a winded response. Over the hills to the right I see movement.  Wishing for Kirico's song I begin an incantation that I keep memorized for those times that we are not hunting together.  I complete the cantrip and feel the pain as my bones go soft and rearrange their pattern.  The sensation of hair growing at a stupendous rate from every square inch of my skin is indescribable.  Soon it is done and I am running as a sister to the pack.  I whine as I pick up the odor of lizard.  It is nearly overpowering.  Underneath it is the familiar odor of halfling in a can.<P>Using the scent as a guide I follow it quickly across the hills.  Soon I see Gort, his short legs a blur as they try to keep up with his magical boots.  Tunare be praised that he had those boots for right behind him, almost literally snapping at his heels was a huge dragon.  His eyes glittering like the opals in the figurine.  Slowly, inexorably, the dragon was drawing nearer to the plucky priest.<P>Drawing upon the power that Tunare has bestowed upon me I called for the plants to reach up and hold fast the monstrous beast.  Alas, the powerful creature tore the roots as if they were but tissue paper.  Quickly, I tried an alternate spell.  Again, the plants reached out, but this time instead of trying to immobilize the great lizard they grasped and grabbed to merely slow it down and allow time for Gort to draw away from it.<P>"Get to Scalpel," I called to Gort.  "I will try to keep our friend entertained."  I saw Gort change direction and head toward Scalpel's body.  The dragon turned, seeking the source of the power that had allied itself with the priest.  Uh, oh.  Using the speed of the wolf I drew it away from Gort.  "Hurry, Gort!  I don't know how long I can keep him."
