<HR size="1" color="#3299CC">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Thank Tunare that reinforcements have arrived!  I glance over my shoulder to see how the dragon is doing.  Dodging swipes of its claws is not what I call a good time.  Cursing softly I see that it has noticed the new arrivals and has quit pursuing me.<P>I circle around back to the party as I take stock of the situation.  It is just like normal, I laugh to myself, everyone rushing around trying to do something and no one coordinating.<P>Vandril takes a claw to the chest- ooo, that has to hurt.  Quickly I cast my biggest healing cantrip.  Amethyst does the same and the expression on Vandril's face as he goes from mortally wounded to hardly scratched is a pleasure to behold.  <P>The dragon has turned to face Gomb.  Easily the most impressive fighter of the group assembled she challenges the monster with her two blades flashing.  Raichu moves in by her side and also lays into the beasty.  I hear Kirico's songs rythmically sounding through the area.  I have heard this combination before- ironically when we were going to challenge the Lady Vox deep in the caverns of permafrost.<P>"Completely healing Gomb," Gort says as he begins his incantation.  I turn my attention to the warriors knowing that until Gort has completed the lengthy ritual that they will be dependent upon my fellow druids and myself for any healing that is required.  I begin to cast my healing spell on Gomb, but before I finish I see that Gort's has completed and her wounds are fading.  I terminate the spell before I waste the results.<P>I stagger as the dragon rears up and we are encompassed in a shower of emerald drops.  The grass turns black in a wide area.  Taking stock, I feel a little sore, but not the major blasting that I expected.  I hear Kirico's songs again and smile.<P>"Train of .... Bentoveroids.... coming from the north." McDuffy shouts. What manner of bizarre creatures are these I wonder.  I take a quick glance and see the creatures with the long arms and ape-like gait.  I shudder as I turn back to the fight.  That is all we needed- more things to fight.<P>"Jaia, please fill me with the Spirit of the Wolf,"  Kirico sits down next to me as I begin the spell.  It used to surprise me that he would want to move like the wolf when with his songs he can move so much faster.  Then he explained that he could only sing so many songs and while he didn't like moving so slow it was still faster than most of our opponents.<P>I see Kirico take out his horn and run toward the onrushing monsters.  He puts the horn to his lips and out comes a horrible dischordant tune.  Reminiscent of claws on slate I am glad that it isn't aimed my direction.  I see the creatures scream in agony and clap their oversize hands to their ears.  Half of them turn to follow Kirico, but the other half are running straight towards Gort!  I am readying a spell when I hear McDuffy calling upon the earth itself to rise up and smite the group.<P>"Darling, can you come give me some help here?" I hear Kirico's voice in my head.<P>"On my way," I send him a quick return thought.<P>"I have to go give Kirico a hand with the bentoveroids.  I will be back as soon as I can.  Amethyste you and Nutryneaux are the only backup healers- McDuffy is meditating."<P>Quickly I run on my four paws over the hill where I saw Kirico heading last.  As I crest the hill I have to laugh.  He is leading them on a merry chase on the other side down by a large stream.  My laughter fades as I see one of the creatures reach out and rake his back ripping through his cloak and drawing furrows of blood through the chinks in armor beneath.  With a burst of speed he lengthens his lead.<P>I can tell that he is still in pretty good shape, but inevitably he will be forced to slow down as the loss of blood increases.  The creatures are not doing very well either, thank goodness, with blood flowing from their ears in copious amounts.  I scan the surrounding territory looking for ideas.<P>Upstream I see that the small river comes from between two steep banks- almost a small cliff.  I smile.  <P>I run over to the bank and quickly swim to the other side.  I position myself on the steep bank and take out my spell book.  McDuffy had the right idea, but this is a much better place.  I scan the spell and lock it into my memory.<P>"Run them upstream along the bank," I tell Kirico.  "Go fast and get some distance on them."  He doesn't reply, but I see him straighten out the circle he has been running in and head in the direction I desire.<P>I see him lengthening his lead and I begin the simple incantation.  As the wierd creatures run under the towering bank the magic takes effect.  The earth rips asunder and huge cracks open up beneath the bentoveroids feet.  With a look of panic they attempt to leap over them.  With a rumble the entire banks splits and comes down upon their heads.  <P>Anxiously, I wait for the dust to clear.  The effect had been more than I expected and I was afraid that Kirico might have been caught in the mini avalance of dirt and rock.  Suddenly he is at my side crooning the melody that helps my thoughts focus easier.<P>"We better head back to the other fight and see what is going on," he says as if nothing has happened.  The melody changes and I feel the cuts and scratches closing, healing from his song.<P>"I hope they are still alive."  I say.  We hurry across the water and over the hill.<P>
<br>
